commentText: Props for mentioning immigration.   A perpetual labour surplus maintained by open borders; is the most basic and obvious reason why wages are driven down and the cost of living is driven up. It doesn't take a genius to figure out that if you increase the competition for a limited supply of jobs, for a limited supply of housing, you bid down the value of labour and up the price of a home.  Latest house building figures is 170k houses were built in the year ending June 2019, that doesn't even cover Net immigration; never mind those also born here... and we wonder why housing is so expensive, even with central bank rates at historical lows?  It's something so obvious that immigration is often rated one of the big issues leading up to votes and elections, because everyone can see this. videoTitle: Why UK Wages Are So Low
videoDescription: Wages and salaries for many people in the UK are RIDICULOUSLY low. This completely sucks, but why is that? It seems that ...
commentText: The UK is a very high wage economy especially at the lower end. Employment is at its highest on record and unemployment is at its lowest on record meanwhile inflation is also super low. Ex-pat intake currently doubles the population growth rate from 0.25-0.5% but on aggregate that adds to the GDP growth rate by at least 0.25% - we can pick and choose which ex-pats to take but not who's born here. Universities are our centres of science, innovaton, research and development - economic growth comes from them! A significent number of ex-pats come here on Tier 1 visas - literally coming here to invest (all too often in propert speculation but hey-ho) - and Tier 2 visas - an employer is so desperate to find someone they're prepared to go through all that hassle to hire them from overseas! We have one of the best education systems in the world, people have always complained about the things you complain about but edcuation hasn't changed much for the last 100 years and you are somewhat overexeggeratin/straw manning with that argument. Most benefits go to people who are working to help out the lowest paid, prevent poverty, and reduce inequality (yes, inequality is bad, it causes civil unrest, price instability, excludes the "other half", doesn't help democracy). Warrenn Buffett is very pro-this sort of thing (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S6irBmOnQEc) because it's fair. Even though it seems wrong that effectively low wage paying employers are being subsidised by the state, you could also see the welfare state as a way of redistributing wealth from the most profitable and stable sectors of the economy to perhaps less profitable and stable sectors - this helps keeps the economy diverse and prevents us "losing" workers and businesses to poverty when recession or inflation hit. This also keeps people in work and occupied and at the very least prevents idolness. For example, Thatcher (love or hate her) did destroy the industires that many towns across the North and Midlands depended on - entire commuinities were plunged into worklessness, idolness, and all the problems that go with that ever since. It is cheaper and easier to subsidise, at least while those towns find ways to replace old industrial jobs, than to try and undo the damage of a town losing its livlihood. These industries did not deserve to die simply because times were tough (i.e. double digit inflation). The UK should stand for more than profits. The welfare state also makes it easier for start-ups and SMEs, by making staff cheaper for them (at the expense of perhaps larger, more established, more profitable, more stable businesses and sectors). SMEs, everything from your local newsagents to a company like Swizzels or Iceland or Gym Shark, account for 99% of businesses and more than half of GDP, and they are where the real innovation and growth come from. Most jobs that have been "lost" have been lost to the higher inflation of the 70s and 80s, and to technology - NOT to ex-pat intake or globalisation. It is difficult, expensive, and far more risky to move jobs abroad - it is a last resort. No-one knows what skills are going to be needed 10 years in future. The arguments you mentioned about education have been going on for CENTURIES (Einstein made some similar remarks) - it's now new, don't worry, education is better than none (example: all human history). Lower taxes do not, and never have encouraged start-ups (although not having stupid anti-landlord taxes would be nice). People will start businesses and thrive regardless of the tax rate - if it's the same for everyone the economy will rebalance and adjust accordingly. Taxes are actually very low and very easy to manage compared to the US and Europe, we're a very business friendly country (https://tradingeconomics.com/united-kingdom/ease-of-doing-business). i.e. in the US there's an entire industry of tax advisors, in the UK we don't need that. We also have the NHS so no-one can't afford healthcare and everyone can live and work and save and spend and invest and rent longer.   I think what the economy really needs is: 1. less outsourcing of services, not so much offshoring, rather, stop paying businesses to do jobs instead of hiring someone to do it 2. less managers 3. MUCH more affordable housing   I agree that too many students are being conned into wasting 3 years of their youth destroying their future (university). I agree about point 4 as per my ramble above. I agree that the UK is "over" globalised - 76% of FTSE 100 earnings coming from overseas vs 44% for the S&P 500 in the US. It's wonderful that we are this global centre of business, but I don't likw how dependent on trade we are. I would like to see government focus on the domestic economy rather than going on about Brexit, trade deals and exporting - we export plenty we just happen to import a bit more because we're a developed modern consumerist 80% service economy that can only supply 60% of our food needs.   I don't agree that these problems are specific to the UK. The US has all of these problems but much, much worse (https://www.ted.com/talks/robert_gordon_the_death_of_innovation_the_end_of_growth?language=en). University is seen as "normal" whereas in the UK it's only 40% who go, huge student debt (UK student loans system isn't a loan it's an extra tax), huge high school dropout rate compared with UK (we don't really have one), huge crime rate compared to UK (in spite of recent heardlines we're as peaceful and safe as Europe and Japan), higher inequality, even more foreign property speculation.   *my points about ex-pat intake are ON AGGREGATE, yes, by ex-pat intake I mean immigration   I'm done :)   - this is intended to be a healthy disagreement/debate
